04511nam a22005535i 9780813555959DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19901990nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135559597 a10.36019/97808135559592doi  a(DE-B1597)529789  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aFAM0000002bisacsh1 aRiessman, Catherine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDivorce Talk :bWomen and Men Make Sense of Personal Relationships /cCatherine Riessman. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[1990] 4cÂ©1990  a1 online resource (292 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tCHAPTER 1 Making Sense of Divorce: Personal Meaning in a Social Context -- tCHAPTER 2 Mourning Different Dreams: Gender and the Companionate Marriage -- tCHAPTER 3 The Teller's Problem: Four Narrative Accounts of Divorce -- tCHAPTER 4 Personal Trauma in Women and Men: The Private Experience of Social Trouble -- tCHAPTER 5 Starting a New Life: The Positive Consequences of Divorce -- tCHAPTER 6 Divorce Is Here to Stay: What Can We Learn from It? -- tAPPENDIX A Narrative about Methods -- tNOTES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTaking a new look at divorce in America, Catherine Reissman shows how divorce is socially shared, and how it takes crucially different forms for women and men. Drawing on interviews with adults who are divorcing, she treats their accounts as texts to be interpreted, as templates for understanding contemporary beliefs about personal relationships. Riessman looks at the ideology of the companionate marriage: husband and wife should be each other's closest companion, and in marriage one should achieve emotial intimacy and sexual fulfillment. These beliefs imply a level of equality that rarely exists. In reality, most wives are subordinate to their husbands, most husbands want neither "deep talk" nor small talk that women want, and many husbands resent their wife's ties to kin and friends. To explain divorce, women and men construct gendered visions of what marriage should provide, and at the same time they mourn gender divisions and blame their divorces on them. Riessman examines the stories people tell about their marriages--the protagonists, inciting conditions, and culminating events--and how these narrative structures provide ways to persuade both teller and listener that divorce was justified. Although divorce is invariably stressful, many people believe that men suffer less than women. This is an artifact of what Riessman calls the "feminization of psychological distress"--traditional ways of measuring distress reflect women's idioms, not men's. Departing from a literature that casts divorce in only negative terms, she finds paradoxically that women sense rewards, even as they report hardship. There is a shakeup in gender roles, and women more than men feel they gain a fuller idea of who they are. The author allows us to enter the points of view of her subjects, while her analytic approach makes links between the self and society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aFAMILY & RELATIONSHIPS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311066333440uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081355595940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813555959423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813555959/original  a978-3-11-066333-4  Rutgers University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles